      "text": "Climate change is one of the most pressing issues of our time. Global temperatures have risen by approximately 1.1 degrees Celsius since pre-industrial times, leading to more frequent extreme weather events, rising sea levels, and loss of biodiversity.\n\nScientists agree that the primary cause is the emission of greenhouse gases — particularly carbon dioxide from burning fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas. While governments and corporations bear the greatest responsibility for tackling this crisis, individuals can also make a meaningful difference.\n\nOne of the most impactful personal choices is diet. Studies show that reducing meat consumption — particularly beef — can significantly lower one's carbon footprint, as livestock farming produces large amounts of methane, a powerful greenhouse gas. Choosing plant-based meals even two or three days a week can make a real difference.\n\nTransportation is another key area. Flying and driving private cars are among the most carbon-intensive activities. Choosing public transport, cycling, or walking when possible can substantially reduce emissions.\n\nCritics argue that individual actions are too small to matter when corporations produce the vast majority of global emissions. This is a valid point. However, consumer choices collectively influence corporate behaviour, and civic engagement — voting, protesting, contacting representatives — can drive systemic change.\n\nThe climate crisis requires action at every level. Individual responsibility and systemic change are not mutually exclusive — both are essential.",
